ball)|Nationalliga A]] club [[FC Basel Frauen|FC Basel]] and the [[Austria women's national football team|Austria women's national team]].<ref>{{UEFA player|id=250056779|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMayr was raised in [[Brunnthal]].<ref name=KJ/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayr, Elisabeth}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women's association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Austrian women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Austria women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:Kansas Jayhawks women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Nationalliga A (women's football) players]]\n[[Category:FC Basel Frauen players]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate<!-- women's --> footballers]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:German women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Munich]]\n[[Category:People from Munich (district)<!--  Brunnthal -->]]\n[[Category:German people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:Frauen-Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Bayer 04 Leverkusen (women) players]]\n[[Category:2. Frauen-Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:FC Bayern Munich<!-- II --> (women) players]]\n[[Category:German expatriate<!-- women's --> footballers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n\n\n{{Austria-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Elisabeth Mayr\n| image          = Elisabeth Mayr 20180513.jpg\n| image_size     = 300px\n| caption        = Mayr in May 2018\n| fullname       =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1996|1|18}}<ref name=SW>{{Soccerway|id=273224|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[Munich]], Germany<ref name=KJ>{{Cite web|url=https://kuathletics.com/roster/eli-mayr/|title=Eli Mayr|website=Kansas Jayhawks|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| height         = 1.70 m<ref name=KJ/>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=SW/>\n| currentclub    = [[FC Basel Frauen|Basel]]\n| clubnumber     = 31\n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| collegeyears1  = 2014\n| college1       = [[Kansas Jayhawks]]\n| collegecaps1   = | collegegoals1 = \n| years1         = 2012\u20132014\n| clubs1         = [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern Munich II]]\n| caps1          = 22\n| goals1         = 8\n| years2         = 2015\u20132018\n| clubs2         = [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern Munich II]]\n| caps2          = 45\n| goals2         = 22\n| years3         = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs3         = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen (women)|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| caps3          = 21\n| goals3         = 3\n| years4         = 2019\u2013\n| clubs4         = [[FC Basel Frauen|Basel]]\n| caps4          = \n| goals4         = \n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| nationalteam1  = {{Nwftu|17|Germany}}\n| nationalcaps1  = 5\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam2  = [[Austria women's national football team|Austria]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 7\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| pcupdate = 12 May 2019\n| ntupdate = 12 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Elisabeth \u201cEli\u201d Mayr''' (born 18 January 1996) is a German-born Austrian [[women's association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for Swiss [[Nationalliga A (women's football)|Nationalliga A]] club [[FC Basel Frauen|FC Basel]] and the [[Austria women's national football team|Austria women's national team]].<ref>{{UEFA player|id=250056779|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMayr was raised in [[Brunnthal]].<ref name=KJ/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayr, Elisabeth}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women's association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Austrian women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Austria women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:Kansas Jayhawks women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Nationalliga A (women's football) players]]\n[[Category:FC Basel Frauen players]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate<!-- women's --> footballers]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:German women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Munich]]\n[[Category:People from Munich (district)<!--  Brunnthal -->]]\n[[Category:German people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:Frauen-Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Bayer 04 Leverkusen (women) players]]\n[[Category:2. Frauen-Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:FC Bayern Munich<!-- II --> (women) players]]\n[[Category:German expatriate<!-- women's --> footballers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisabeth_Mayr"}
{"title_page": "Fort Zumwalt Park", "text_new": "{{short description|Park in O'Fallon, Missouri, U.S.}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n| name =Fort Zumwalt Park\n| image = Reconstructed Ft. Zumwalt 2017.jpg\n| caption = Reconstructed Fort Zumwalt, 2017\n| location= [[O'Fallon, Missouri]]\n| locmapin = Missouri#USA\n| area = {{convert|48|acres}}\n| built = 1798 (Zumwalt),<br />1884 (Heald)\n| rebuilt = 2015 (Zumwalt)\n| restored = 2001 (Heald)\n| restored_by = O'Fallon Community Foundation\n| governing_body = City of O'Fallon\n}}\n'''Fort Zumwalt Park''' is a park in [[O'Fallon, Missouri]] that features the rebuilt homestead fort of Jacob Zumwalt.\n\nThe park's total area is {{convert|48|acre}} with {{convert|4|acre|adj=on}} Lake Whetsel, a picnic pavilion, a shelter house and a children's playground with equipment.  The lake is open for fishing from February though October (7am\u20137pm).<ref>{{cite web|title=Fort Tours: Fort Zumwalt|url=http://www.forttours.com/pages/fortzumwalt.asp}}</ref>  Fort Zumwalt Park hosts O'Fallon's annual ''Celebration of Lights'', a drive-through display of light decorations, every [[Christmas]] season,<ref>{{cite web|title=St. Louis Region Holidays|url=http://www.lasr.net/travel/region.php?Region_ID=MO10&VE=Y&EventCategory=Holidays}}</ref> and is home to the St. Charles Model Railroad Club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stcharlesrailroadclub.org/club-info |title=Club Info |publisher=St. Charles Model Railroad Club |access-date=April 12, 2018 }}</ref>  The site also includes the Darius Heald Home.<ref name=scout>{{cite web|title=St. Charles County Outdoors: Fort Zumwalt|url=http://stcharlescountyoutdoors.org/docs/parkdetail.cfm?park_ID=96&park_City=7|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728055207/http://www.stcharlescountyoutdoors.org/docs/parkdetail.cfm?park_ID=96&park_City=7|archive-date=July 28, 2011}}</ref> Formerly a state park since 1939, the State of Missouri sold the property to the City of O'Fallon in 1978 for one dollar.<ref name=wmark>{{cite web|title=Fort Zumwalt Park&nbsp;\u2013 O'Fallon, MO Waymark|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM4NBD}}</ref> The Heald Home was restored in 2001 and reconstruction of Zumwalt's fort was completed in 2015.\n\n==Zumwalt's Fort==\nThe hill on which Jacob Zumwalt built his home was part of a nearly {{convert|384|acre|adj=on}} Spanish [[land grant]] that [[History of Missouri#Spanish settlement and government|he accepted in 1796]], with land on both sides of [[Belleau Creek]]. Zumwalt was a Revolutionary War veteran, one of only a few who settled in [[Saint Charles County, Missouri]]. His family originally came from Pennsylvania and spent some time in Kentucky before moving to Missouri.<ref name=ohs>{{cite web |url=https://ofallonmohistory.com/tag/zumwalts-fort/ |title=Jacob Zumwalt and Zumwalt's Fort |access-date=April 7, 2018 |publisher=O'Fallon Historical Society }}</ref>\n\nZumwalt's extended family helped him complete the first section of the home in 1798, with additions made in following years.  It is believed to have been the first hewn log house north of the [[Missouri River]], and its four rooms, stone foundation, double-fireplace, and other [[Pennsylvania Dutch|Pennsylvania German]] construction details set it apart from other homes. The family was of Methodist faith and the first [[Methodism#Sacraments|Methodist sacrament]] in Missouri was in the home in 1807.<ref name=\"ohs\" />\n\nThe home was called \"Zumwalt's Fort\" because area families would gather there for protection from raids during the [[War of 1812]]. There were seven such homestead forts in St. Charles County. Area fighting with Native Americans ended by 1815, when peace treaties were signed nearby.<ref name=\"ohs\" />\n\n===After Zumwalt===\nZumwalt raised ten children from two wives,<ref name=\"ohs\" /> and in 1817, moved adjacent to a son-in-law in [[Callaway County, Missouri]], where he died in 1820.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/images/stories/Reading/01a%20Addendum%20and%20Correction%20to%20History%20of%20Jacob%20Zumwalt.pdf |title=Addendum and Correction to History of Jacob Zumwalt's Fort |website=O'Fallon Community Foundation |access-date=April 11, 2018 }}</ref>  After the Heald family owned the land for nearly the next 100 years, it was sold outside the family in 1914 and then split among three owners.  The portion that contained the fort was sold to Fred Gentemann who converted it into use as a barn. In September 1929, primarily through efforts by two Heald family members, a commemorative marker was placed along nearby [[U.S. Highway 40#Missouri|U.S. Highway 40]] (now also known as [[Interstate 64 in Missouri|Interstate 64]]) to share the history of the site. In 1936, a state historical group presented resolutions to petition the state legislature to buy {{convert|87|acres}} surrounding the fort for a state park. The following year, funds to expand the state park system were approved and in 1938, the state filed condemnation proceedings to acquire {{convert|40.63|acres}} for the park, which it bought from three owners (including Gentemann) for $9,000 in early 1939.<ref name=Weil>{{cite web |title=Historical Background of Fort Zumwalt |website=O'Fallon Community Foundation |first=Andrew |last=Weil |pages=36\u201339 |access-date=April 10, 2018 |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/images/stories/Reading/03%20History.pdf#page=36 }}</ref>\n\nInitially, the state park was used mostly by O'Fallon residents, though it gradually became a popular camping and relaxation point for travelers on U.S. 40 (and later [[Interstate 70 in Missouri|Interstate 70]]). The central chimney was rebuilt in 1960, apparently from only reclaimed pieces of the fort's foundations as no stone was ordered for the job.  As part of an [[survey (archaeology)|archaeological survey]] of all its parks, and with initial plans for reconstruction of the fort, the state of Missouri sponsored excavations around parts of the fort for several weeks in 1975, the findings of which suggested the prior presence of a [[smoke house]] and [[blacksmith]]ing activity. In 1978, the state sold the park to the City of O'Fallon for $1, requiring that it continue to be maintained as a public park. In 2005, with permission by the city, the O'Fallon Community Foundation resumed long-delayed plans to restore the fort and hired the Archaeology Research Center of St. Louis to complete excavations around it.<ref name=Weil />\n\n===Reconstruction and legacy===\nAll that remained of the original Zumwalt home as of September 2008 was its internal stone chimney with two fireplaces, one on either side.<ref name=\"wmark\" /> In 2008, the O'Fallon Community Foundation began work on the reconstruction of Zumwalt's home. On September 30, 2009, the foundation held a ribbon cutting to celebrate the completion of the first phase of the reconstruction of Jacob Zumwalt's homestead fort.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/home/zumwalts-fort?showall=&start=3 |title=October 2009 Update |access-date=April 12, 2018 |publisher=O'Fallon Community Foundation }}</ref> The plan was to have all three phases of Zumwalt's log structures reconstructed by 2012 in timing with the bicentennial of the War of 1812. By the end of 2013, however, delays had put the completion time in doubt. The reconstructed fort opened in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofallon.mo.us/zumwalts-fort |title=Zumwalt's Fort |publisher=City of O'Fallon |access-date=April 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe local [[Fort Zumwalt School District]] R-II was renamed after this fort in 1966; the district's [[Fort Zumwalt North High School|first high school]] has been named for the fort since 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fz.k12.mo.us/cms/One.aspx?portalId=191707&pageId=504431 |title=Facts at a Glance |publisher=Fort Zumwalt School District R-II |access-date=April 7, 2018 }}</ref> A total of four high schools in the district now have the Fort Zumwalt name, appended with their relative compass directions. In the 1970s, a spring on the property was dammed to form Lake Whetsel, named for Ed Whetsel, a member of the O'Fallon Parks Board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ofallon.mo.us/parks&rec/fort-zumwalt-park |title=Fort Zumwalt Park |publisher=O'Fallon Parks and Recreation |access-date=April 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Heald Home==\n[[File:The Chicago massacre of 1812 - with illustrations and historical documents (1893) (14804217223).jpg|thumb|Darius Heald in 1893, holding his father's sword among other relics]]\nJacob Zumwalt sold his homestead fort to [[Nathan Heald|Nathan]] and Rebekah Heald for $1000 in 1817.  Their son Darius was born there in 1822 and lived in the homestead for most of his life.  Darius Heald built a new large brick home near the fort in 1884 and called it \"Stony Point\". Its architecture has been referred to as \"German-Italianate-Victorian\"&nbsp;\u2013 primarily of [[German architecture|German construction]], with [[Architecture of Italy|Italian influence]] in the porch columns and balcony railing.  Heald died in 1904 and a tornado destroyed the upper floor of the house in 1915. Before selling the home in 1916, the family rebuilt its upper story with original recovered bricks, though it was about a foot shorter in height.<ref name=heald /> A state park superintendent is known to have lived in the home in 1959. Beginning in 1961, the state removed what had been the Heald's brick smoke house, and took its bricks to [[Arrow Rock, Missouri|Arrow Rock]] for reuse, apparently in restoration of the Dr. Hall House.<ref name=Weil />  After decades of use and nonuse, the Heald house was in need of repair, and was restored in 2001 by the City of O'Fallon and the O'Fallon Community Foundation.<ref name=heald>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/home/heald-house |title=Heald House |publisher=O'Fallon Community Foundation |access-date=April 10, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Fort Zumwalt School District]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ofallon.mo.us/zumwalts-fort Official park homepage]\n*[http://www.looktothepast.com/fort.html ''Look to the Past'' page on Fort Zumwalt, with pictures]\n*[http://www.fz.k12.mo.us/ Fort Zumwalt School District]\n*[http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org O'Fallon Community Foundation]\n\n{{coord|38|47|47|N|90|42|30|W|type:landmark_scale:10000_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Charles County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Former state parks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Forts in Missouri|Zumwalt]]\n[[Category:Parks in St. Charles County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Pre-statehood history of Missouri]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of St. Charles County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:1798 establishments in New Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Park in O'Fallon, Missouri, U.S.}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n| name =Fort Zumwalt Park\n| image = Reconstructed Ft. Zumwalt 2017.jpg\n| caption = Reconstructed Fort Zumwalt, 2017\n| location= [[O'Fallon, Missouri]]\n| locmapin = Missouri#USA\n| area = {{convert|48|acres}}\n| built = 1798 (Zumwalt),<br />1884 (Heald)\n| rebuilt = 2015 (Zumwalt)\n| restored = 2001 (Heald)\n| restored_by = O'Fallon Community Foundation\n| governing_body = City of O'Fallon\n}}\n'''Fort Zumwalt Park''' is a park in [[O'Fallon, Missouri]] that features the rebuilt homestead fort of Jacob Zumwalt.\n\nThe park's total area is {{convert|48|acre}} with {{convert|4|acre|adj=on}} Lake Whetsel, a picnic pavilion, a shelter house and a children's playground with equipment.  The lake is open for fishing from February though October (7am\u20137pm).<ref>{{cite web|title=Fort Tours: Fort Zumwalt|url=http://www.forttours.com/pages/fortzumwalt.asp}}</ref>  Fort Zumwalt Park hosts O'Fallon's annual ''Celebration of Lights'', a drive-through display of light decorations, every [[Christmas]] season,<ref>{{cite web|title=St. Louis Region Holidays|url=http://www.lasr.net/travel/region.php?Region_ID=MO10&VE=Y&EventCategory=Holidays}}</ref> and is home to the St. Charles Model Railroad Club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stcharlesrailroadclub.org/club-info |title=Club Info |publisher=St. Charles Model Railroad Club |access-date=April 12, 2018 }}</ref>  The site also includes the Darius Heald Home.<ref name=scout>{{cite web|title=St. Charles County Outdoors: Fort Zumwalt|url=http://stcharlescountyoutdoors.org/docs/parkdetail.cfm?park_ID=96&park_City=7|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728055207/http://www.stcharlescountyoutdoors.org/docs/parkdetail.cfm?park_ID=96&park_City=7|archive-date=July 28, 2011}}</ref> Formerly a state park since 1939, the State of Missouri sold the property to the City of O'Fallon in 1978 for one dollar.<ref name=wmark>{{cite web|title=Fort Zumwalt Park&nbsp;\u2013 O'Fallon, MO Waymark|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM4NBD}}</ref> The Heald Home was restored in 2001 and reconstruction of Zumwalt's fort was completed in 2015.\n\n==Zumwalt's Fort==\nThe hill on which Jacob Zumwalt built his home was part of a nearly {{convert|384|acre|adj=on}} Spanish [[land grant]] that [[History of Missouri#Spanish settlement and government|he accepted in 1796]], with land on both sides of [[Belleau Creek]]. Zumwalt was a Revolutionary War veteran, one of only a few who settled in [[Saint Charles County, Missouri]]. His family originally came from Pennsylvania and spent some time in Kentucky before moving to Missouri.<ref name=ohs>{{cite web |url=https://ofallonmohistory.com/tag/zumwalts-fort/ |title=Jacob Zumwalt and Zumwalt's Fort |access-date=April 7, 2018 |publisher=O'Fallon Historical Society }}</ref>\n\nZumwalt's extended family helped him complete the first section of the home in 1798, with additions made in following years.  It is believed to have been the first hewn log house north of the [[Missouri River]], and its four rooms, stone foundation, double-fireplace, and other [[Pennsylvania Dutch|Pennsylvania German]] construction details set it apart from other homes. The family was of Methodist faith and the first [[Methodism#Sacraments|Methodist sacrament]] in Missouri was in the home in 1807.<ref name=\"ohs\" />\n\nThe home was called \"Zumwalt's Fort\" because area families would gather there for protection from raids during the [[War of 1812]]. There were seven such homestead forts in St. Charles County. Area fighting with Native Americans ended by 1815, when peace treaties were signed nearby.<ref name=\"ohs\" />\n\nZumwalt raised ten children from two wives,<ref name=\"ohs\" /> and in 1817, moved adjacent to a son-in-law in [[Callaway County, Missouri]], where he died in 1820.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/images/stories/Reading/01a%20Addendum%20and%20Correction%20to%20History%20of%20Jacob%20Zumwalt.pdf |title=Addendum and Correction to History of Jacob Zumwalt's Fort |website=O'Fallon Community Foundation |access-date=April 11, 2018 }}</ref>  After the Heald family owned the land for nearly the next 100 years, it was sold outside the family in 1914 and then split among three owners.  The portion that contained the fort was sold to Fred Gentemann who converted it into use as a barn. In September 1929, primarily through efforts by two Heald family members, a commemorative marker was placed along nearby [[U.S. Highway 40#Missouri|U.S. Highway 40]] (now also known as [[Interstate 64 in Missouri|Interstate 64]]) to share the history of the site. In 1936, a state historical group presented resolutions to petition the state legislature to buy {{convert|87|acres}} surrounding the fort for a state park. The following year, funds to expand the state park system were approved and in 1938, the state filed condemnation proceedings to acquire {{convert|40.63|acres}} for the park, which it bought from three owners (including Gentemann) for $9,000 in early 1939.<ref name=Weil>{{cite web |title=Historical Background of Fort Zumwalt |website=O'Fallon Community Foundation |first=Andrew |last=Weil |pages=36\u201339 |access-date=April 10, 2018 |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/images/stories/Reading/03%20History.pdf#page=36 }}</ref>\n\nInitially, the state park was used mostly by O'Fallon residents, though it gradually became a popular camping and relaxation point for travelers on U.S. 40 (and later [[Interstate 70 in Missouri|Interstate 70]]). The central chimney was rebuilt in 1960, apparently from only reclaimed pieces of the fort's foundations as no stone was ordered for the job.  As part of an [[survey (archaeology)|archaeological survey]] of all its parks, and with initial plans for reconstruction of the fort, the state of Missouri sponsored excavations around parts of the fort for several weeks in 1975, the findings of which suggested the prior presence of a [[smoke house]] and [[blacksmith]]ing activity. In 1978, the state sold the park to the City of O'Fallon for $1, requiring that it continue to be maintained as a public park. In 2005, with permission by the city, the O'Fallon Community Foundation resumed long-delayed plans to restore the fort and hired the Archaeology Research Center of St. Louis to complete excavations around it.<ref name=Weil />\n\nAll that remained of the original Zumwalt home as of September 2008 was its internal stone chimney with two fireplaces, one on either side.<ref name=\"wmark\" /> In 2008, the O'Fallon Community Foundation began work on the reconstruction of Zumwalt's home. On September 30, 2009, the foundation held a ribbon cutting to celebrate the completion of the first phase of the reconstruction of Jacob Zumwalt's homestead fort.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/home/zumwalts-fort?showall=&start=3 |title=October 2009 Update |access-date=April 12, 2018 |publisher=O'Fallon Community Foundation }}</ref> The plan was to have all three phases of Zumwalt's log structures reconstructed by 2012 in timing with the bicentennial of the War of 1812. By the end of 2013, however, delays had put the completion time in doubt. The reconstructed fort opened in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofallon.mo.us/zumwalts-fort |title=Zumwalt's Fort |publisher=City of O'Fallon |access-date=April 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe local [[Fort Zumwalt School District]] R-II was renamed after this fort in 1966; the district's [[Fort Zumwalt North High School|first high school]] has been named for the fort since 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fz.k12.mo.us/cms/One.aspx?portalId=191707&pageId=504431 |title=Facts at a Glance |publisher=Fort Zumwalt School District R-II |access-date=April 7, 2018 }}</ref> A total of four high schools in the district now have the Fort Zumwalt name, appended with their relative compass directions. In the 1970s, a spring on the property was dammed to form Lake Whetsel, named for Ed Whetsel, a member of the O'Fallon Parks Board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ofallon.mo.us/parks&rec/fort-zumwalt-park |title=Fort Zumwalt Park |publisher=O'Fallon Parks and Recreation |access-date=April 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Heald Home==\n[[File:The Chicago massacre of 1812 - with illustrations and historical documents (1893) (14804217223).jpg|thumb|Darius Heald in 1893, holding his father's sword among other relics]]\nJacob Zumwalt sold his homestead fort to [[Nathan Heald|Nathan]] and Rebekah Heald for $1000 in 1817.  Their son Darius was born there in 1822 and lived in the homestead for most of his life.  Darius Heald built a new large brick home near the fort in 1884 and called it \"Stony Point\". Its architecture has been referred to as \"German-Italianate-Victorian\"&nbsp;\u2013 primarily of [[German architecture|German construction]], with [[Architecture of Italy|Italian influence]] in the porch columns and balcony railing.  Heald died in 1904 and a tornado destroyed the upper floor of the house in 1915. Before selling the home in 1916, the family rebuilt its upper story with original recovered bricks, though it was about a foot shorter in height.<ref name=heald /> A state park superintendent is known to have lived in the home in 1959. Beginning in 1961, the state removed what had been the Heald's brick smoke house, and took its bricks to [[Arrow Rock, Missouri|Arrow Rock]] for reuse, apparently in restoration of the Dr. Hall House.<ref name=Weil />  After decades of use and nonuse, the Heald house was in need of repair, and was restored in 2001 by the City of O'Fallon and the O'Fallon Community Foundation.<ref name=heald>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org/home/heald-house |title=Heald House |publisher=O'Fallon Community Foundation |access-date=April 10, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Fort Zumwalt School District]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ofallon.mo.us/zumwalts-fort Official park homepage]\n*[http://www.looktothepast.com/fort.html ''Look to the Past'' page on Fort Zumwalt, with pictures]\n*[http://www.fz.k12.mo.us/ Fort Zumwalt School District]\n*[http://www.ofalloncommunityfoundation.org O'Fallon Community Foundation]\n\n{{coord|38|47|47|N|90|42|30|W|type:landmark_scale:10000_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Charles County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Former state parks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Forts in Missouri|Zumwalt]]\n[[Category:Parks in St. Charles County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Pre-statehood history of Missouri]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of St. Charles County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:1798 establishments in New Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eZumwalt's Fort:added subheadings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Zumwalt_Park"}
{"title_page": "Kaneez Surka", "text_new": "{{short description|South African stand up comedian}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name                 = Kaneez Surka\n| image                =\n| image_size           = \n| alt                  = \n| caption              = \n| pseudonym            = \n| birth_name           = Kaneez Surka\n| native_name          = \n| native_name_lang     = \n| birth_date           = 28 October 1983\n| birth_place          = [[Mthatha]], [[South Africa]]\n| medium               = [[English language|English]]\n| nationality          = [[Indian South Africans]]\n| education            = \n| alma_mater           = [[Rhodes University]]\n| active               = 2006&nbsp;\u2013 present\n| employer             = [[Amazon Prime]]<br/>[[TLC (India)]]\n| genre                = [[Improvisational comedy]]\n| subject              = \n| spouse               = \n| domesticpartner      = \n| children             = \n| parents              = \n| relatives            = \n| notable_work         = [[The Week That Wasn't]]<br>The General Fun Game Show<br>[[All India Bakchod]]<br>[[Comicstaan]]\n| memorials            = \n| signature            = \n| website              = {{url|www.youtube.com/channel/UC6a7TnbzoeggcDscJBrR0kw}}\n| footnotes            = \n| module               = \n}}\n\n'''Kaneez Surka''' is a [[South Africa]]n [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] artist, actor, comedian and a [[YouTuber]] born in gujarati muslim family who works mainly in India. She started her career with the show ''[[The Week That Wasn't]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/people-find-it-easily-digestible-when-guys-are-a-little-crude-comedian-kaneez-surka/story-BwrFZth9a6Dsc8RwXwRilK.html|title=People find it easily digestible when guys are a little crude: Comedian Kaneez Surka|date=2016-12-15|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/kaneez-surka-aib-amazon-prime-video-5172736/|title=Kaneez Surka on stand-up, multiculturalism and political humour|date=2018-05-13|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/kaneez-surka-im-scared-to-do-stand-up-comedy/19633162|title=Kaneez Surka: I m scared to do stand-up comedy|date=2018-07-24|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://t2online.com/lifestyle/from-metoo-to-bolly-humour-kaneez-surka-really-random-rapid-fire/cid/18784|title=From #MeToo to Bolly humour: Kaneez Surka takes our really random rapid fire|website=t2online.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/watch-mallika-dua-kaneez-surka-reprise-roles-in-aibs-if-apps-were-people-2-4124807.html|title=Watch: Mallika Dua, Kaneez Surka reprise roles in AIB's If Apps Were People 2- Entertainment News, Firstpost|work=Firstpost|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref> She has performed on various stand up platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/comedienne-kaneez-surka-hosts-three-popular-guests-in-her-game-show/19446155|title=Comedienne Kaneez Surka hosts Sapan Verma, Sahil Shah and RJ Malishka in her game show|date=2018-05-22|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref> She was a judge for the [[Amazon Prime]] stand-up comedy reality show [[Comicstaan (TV series)|Comicstaan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businessofcinema.com/bollywood_news/comicstaans-latest-episode-focuses-on-kaneez-surkas-improv-round/424196|title=Comicstaan's Latest Episode Focuses On Kaneez Surka's Improv Round!|date=2018-07-24|work=Businessofcinema.com|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/en/comicstaans-latest-episode-focuses-on-kaneez-surkas-improve-round|title=Comicstaan's latest episode focuses on Kaneez Surka's improve round!|website=Glamsham|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/hot-on-web/amazon-prime-video-comicstaan-review-the-future-is-pretty-funny|title='Comicstaan' Review: The Future Looks Pretty Funny|work=The Quint|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref> She also hosts an online comedy game show, ''The General Fun Game Show'' on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/youtube-series-comedians-books-reading-the-botcast-books-on-toast/18071158|title=Comedians talk about books they read in new YouTube series|date=2017-03-14|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/others/things-to-do/things-to-do-in-mumbai-today/articleshow/65409027.cms|title=Things to do in Mumbai today|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKaneez Surka was born and raised in [[Mthatha]], [[South Africa]]. She studied in [[Diocesan School for Girls, Grahamstown|DSG]], Graham School and attended [[Rhodes University]], where she obtained a Bachelor of Arts in law and psychology.<ref name=\"Kale 2018\">{{Cite web|url=http://astray.in/interviews/kaneez-surka|title=Kaneez Surka|last=Kale|first=Arun|date=26 August 2014|website=Astray|access-date= 12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSurka was part of the Mumbai improv scene since 2009.<ref name=\"Kale 2018\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/video/comedy/the-rising-stars-of-comedy/laughter-therapy-with-the-rising-stars-of-comedy-367904|title=Laughter Therapy With The Rising Stars of Comedy|date=May 18, 2015|website=NDTV}}</ref> Her initial work in Mumbai was with Divya Palat's Imps troupe.<ref name=\"Kale 2018\" /> Surka was co-director of a Mumbai-based story-telling club \"Tall Tales\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/tell-stories-at-tall-tales-mumbais-newest-storytelling-club/214135|title=Tell stories at Tall Tales, Mumbai's newest storytelling club|last=Gianani|first=Kareena|date=May 19, 2013|website=Mid Day}}</ref> in 2013.\n\nShe achieved mainstream popularity on the satirical news show [[The Week That Wasn't]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/others/sunday-read/small-talk-the-improv-lady/articleshow/58556388.cms|title=Small talk: The improv lady|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> on [[CNN-News18]] (formerly CNN-IBN). She also worked with Weirdass Comedy, a [[Vir Das]] venture and then began collaborating with<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/life-style/nothing-half-baked-about-it/111262.html|title=Nothing half-baked about it|last=Singh|first=Jasmine|date=Jul 26, 2015|work=The Tribune|access-date=}}</ref> and making appearances in several [[All India Bakchod]] videos including roles such as Clitika from 'A woman's besties', 'Honest wedding', 'Honest Bars' and the Instagram character from 'If Apps were people'. She was also a judge for shows such as [[Comicstaan]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/comicstaan-tanmay-bhat-kanan-gill-kaneez-surka-on-amazons-upcoming-show-and-all-things-comedy-4646661.html|title=Comictaan|work=firstpost|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7336778/|title=Comicstaan|work=IMDB|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref> and 'Improv All Stars' for [[Amazon Prime]] and [[Queens of Comedy]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/richa-chadha-rohan-joshi-and-kaneez-surka-roped-in-to-judge-queens-of-comedy/articleshow/59673869.cms|title=Queens Of Comedy|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=2018-07-20}}</ref> for [[TLC (India)|TLC]]. Surka is part of an improv group called \"The Improvisers\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/kaneez-surka-aib-amazon-prime-video-5172736/|title=Kaneez Surka on stand-up, multiculturalism and political humour|last=Singh|first=Anvita|date=May 13, 2018|website=The Indian Express|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> along with [[Abish Mathew]], [[Kanan Gill]], and [[Kenny Sebastian]] on [[Amazon Prime Video]]. She also teaches the art of improv comedy, proving her comedic skills by being a judge in [[Amazon Prime|Amazon Prime's]] stand-up comedy reality show [[Comicstaan]].<ref name=\"Kale 2018\" />\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Web<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8595003/|title=Kaneez Surka|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref> ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Platform\n!Name\n!Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|TV Series\n|The Living Room\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|TV Mini-Series\n|How Insensitive! By Kanan Gill\n|Plays various side-characters\n|-\n|2015-2016\n|YouTube\n|AIB Honest Series\n|AIB: Honest Bars & Restaurants Part 1, 2, 3\nAIB: Honest Indian Weddings Part 1, 2\n|-\n|2016\n|TV Series\n|Better Life Foundation\n|Plays Vashma Chandi (1 episode)\n|-\n|2017\n|YouTube Series\n|Son of Abish\n|Season 3 with [[Swara Bhaskar]] (Episode 7)<ref>{{Citation|last=Abish Mathew|title=Son Of Abish feat. Kaneez Surka & Swara Bhaskar|date=2017-11-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=quAWroEKQUI|access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Amazon Prime]]\n|The Improvisers: Something from Nothing\n|Herself\n|-\n|[[Comicstaan]] Season 1\n|Herself - Judge\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Amazon Prime]]\n|[[Comicstaan]] Season 2\n|Herself - Judge\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surka, Kaneez}}\n[[Category:Indian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian women comedians]]\n[[Category:Indian Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Indian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:South African people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Rhodes University alumni]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:South African comedians]]\n[[Category:Women humorists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African stand up comedian}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name                 = Kaneez Surka\n| image                =\n| image_size           = \n| alt          