rka-im-scared-to-do-stand-up-comedy/19633162|title=Kaneez Surka: I m scared to do stand-up comedy|date=2018-07-24|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://t2online.com/lifestyle/from-metoo-to-bolly-humour-kaneez-surka-really-random-rapid-fire/cid/18784|title=From #MeToo to Bolly humour: Kaneez Surka takes our really random rapid fire|website=t2online.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/watch-mallika-dua-kaneez-surka-reprise-roles-in-aibs-if-apps-were-people-2-4124807.html|title=Watch: Mallika Dua, Kaneez Surka reprise roles in AIB's If Apps Were People 2- Entertainment News, Firstpost|work=Firstpost|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref> She has performed on various stand up platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/comedienne-kaneez-surka-hosts-three-popular-guests-in-her-game-show/19446155|title=Comedienne Kaneez Surka hosts Sapan Verma, Sahil Shah and RJ Malishka in her game show|date=2018-05-22|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref> She was a judge for the [[Amazon Prime]] stand-up comedy reality show [[Comicstaan (TV series)|Comicstaan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businessofcinema.com/bollywood_news/comicstaans-latest-episode-focuses-on-kaneez-surkas-improv-round/424196|title=Comicstaan's Latest Episode Focuses On Kaneez Surka's Improv Round!|date=2018-07-24|work=Businessofcinema.com|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/en/comicstaans-latest-episode-focuses-on-kaneez-surkas-improve-round|title=Comicstaan's latest episode focuses on Kaneez Surka's improve round!|website=Glamsham|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/hot-on-web/amazon-prime-video-comicstaan-review-the-future-is-pretty-funny|title='Comicstaan' Review: The Future Looks Pretty Funny|work=The Quint|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref> She also hosts an online comedy game show, ''The General Fun Game Show'' on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/youtube-series-comedians-books-reading-the-botcast-books-on-toast/18071158|title=Comedians talk about books they read in new YouTube series|date=2017-03-14|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/others/things-to-do/things-to-do-in-mumbai-today/articleshow/65409027.cms|title=Things to do in Mumbai today|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKaneez Surka was born and raised in [[Mthatha]], [[South Africa]]. She studied in [[Diocesan School for Girls, Grahamstown|DSG]], Graham School and attended [[Rhodes University]], where she obtained a Bachelor of Arts in law and psychology.<ref name=\"Kale 2018\">{{Cite web|url=http://astray.in/interviews/kaneez-surka|title=Kaneez Surka|last=Kale|first=Arun|date=26 August 2014|website=Astray|access-date= 12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSurka was part of the Mumbai improv scene since 2009.<ref name=\"Kale 2018\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/video/comedy/the-rising-stars-of-comedy/laughter-therapy-with-the-rising-stars-of-comedy-367904|title=Laughter Therapy With The Rising Stars of Comedy|date=May 18, 2015|website=NDTV}}</ref> Her initial work in Mumbai was with Divya Palat's Imps troupe.<ref name=\"Kale 2018\" /> Surka was co-director of a Mumbai-based story-telling club \"Tall Tales\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/tell-stories-at-tall-tales-mumbais-newest-storytelling-club/214135|title=Tell stories at Tall Tales, Mumbai's newest storytelling club|last=Gianani|first=Kareena|date=May 19, 2013|website=Mid Day}}</ref> in 2013.\n\nShe achieved mainstream popularity on the satirical news show [[The Week That Wasn't]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/others/sunday-read/small-talk-the-improv-lady/articleshow/58556388.cms|title=Small talk: The improv lady|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> on [[CNN-News18]] (formerly CNN-IBN). She also worked with Weirdass Comedy, a [[Vir Das]] venture and then began collaborating with<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/life-style/nothing-half-baked-about-it/111262.html|title=Nothing half-baked about it|last=Singh|first=Jasmine|date=Jul 26, 2015|work=The Tribune|access-date=}}</ref> and making appearances in several [[All India Bakchod]] videos including roles such as Clitika from 'A woman's besties', 'Honest wedding', 'Honest Bars' and the Instagram character from 'If Apps were people'. She was also a judge for shows such as [[Comicstaan]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/comicstaan-tanmay-bhat-kanan-gill-kaneez-surka-on-amazons-upcoming-show-and-all-things-comedy-4646661.html|title=Comictaan|work=firstpost|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7336778/|title=Comicstaan|work=IMDB|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref> and 'Improv All Stars' for [[Amazon Prime]] and [[Queens of Comedy]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/richa-chadha-rohan-joshi-and-kaneez-surka-roped-in-to-judge-queens-of-comedy/articleshow/59673869.cms|title=Queens Of Comedy|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=2018-07-20}}</ref> for [[TLC (India)|TLC]]. Surka is part of an improv group called \"The Improvisers\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/kaneez-surka-aib-amazon-prime-video-5172736/|title=Kaneez Surka on stand-up, multiculturalism and political humour|last=Singh|first=Anvita|date=May 13, 2018|website=The Indian Express|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> along with [[Abish Mathew]], [[Kanan Gill]], and [[Kenny Sebastian]] on [[Amazon Prime Video]]. She also teaches the art of improv comedy, proving her comedic skills by being a judge in [[Amazon Prime|Amazon Prime's]] stand-up comedy reality show [[Comicstaan]].<ref name=\"Kale 2018\" />\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Web<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8595003/|title=Kaneez Surka|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref> ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Platform\n!Name\n!Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|TV Series\n|The Living Room\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|TV Mini-Series\n|How Insensitive! By Kanan Gill\n|Plays various side-characters\n|-\n|2015-2016\n|YouTube\n|AIB Honest Series\n|AIB: Honest Bars & Restaurants Part 1, 2, 3\nAIB: Honest Indian Weddings Part 1, 2\n|-\n|2016\n|TV Series\n|Better Life Foundation\n|Plays Vashma Chandi (1 episode)\n|-\n|2017\n|YouTube Series\n|Son of Abish\n|Season 3 with [[Swara Bhaskar]] (Episode 7)<ref>{{Citation|last=Abish Mathew|title=Son Of Abish feat. Kaneez Surka & Swara Bhaskar|date=2017-11-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=quAWroEKQUI|access-date=2018-10-17}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Amazon Prime]]\n|The Improvisers: Something from Nothing\n|Herself\n|-\n|[[Comicstaan]] Season 1\n|Herself - Judge\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Amazon Prime]]\n|[[Comicstaan]] Season 2\n|Herself - Judge\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surka, Kaneez}}\n[[Category:Indian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian women comedians]]\n[[Category:Indian Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Indian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:South African people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Rhodes University alumni]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:South African comedians]]\n[[Category:Women humorists]]\n", "name_user": "139.216.197.92", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaneez_Surka"}
{"title_page": "Shimshon ben Mordechai of Slonim", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rabbi Shimshon ben Mordechai of Slonim\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 1734 or 1736\n| birth_place        = Lithuania, Poland-Lithuania\n| death_date         = 1794\n| death_place        = K\u00f6nigsberg, Prussia\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = Samson of Slonim\n| occupation         = Av Beit Din of Slonim and K\u00f6nigsberg, scientist, astronomer, philosopher, mathematician\n| years_active       = 1769-1794\n| era                = 18th-century philosophy\n| known_for          = Haskalah Movement, Misnagdim Movement, Approbation of Sefer Oklidus\n| movement           = Haskalah, Misnagdim\n| opponents          = Hasidic Jews\n| spouse             = Basha bat Ze'ev Wolf\n| children           = Gershon Zelig of Kosava\n| father             = Mordechai\n| family             = Karelitz\n| Influence          = Vilna Gaon\n}}\n'''Shimshon (Samson) ben Mordechai of Slonim''' (c. 1734/1736 \u2013 1794), was an 18th-century rabbi, philosopher, mathematician, and scientist. He was one of the  leaders of [[Haskalah]] and the [[Misnagdim]], and was greatly influenced by the Vilna Gaon. He was the [[Av Beit Din]] of [[Slonim]] and [[K\u00f6nigsberg]] and is thought to have been descended from Shimshon Loew ben Bezalel, the [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel|Maharal of Prague]]'s brother through his grandson, [[Samson ben Pesah Ostropoli]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Pinkas Slonim [Memorial Book of Slonim]|last=Lichtenstein|first=Kalman|publisher=Irgun \u02bbole Slonim be-Yi\u015bra\u02bcel|year=1961|isbn=|volume=1|location=Tel Aviv|pages=33\u201339}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and early adulthood ==\nNot that much is known about his early life. We do know that he was born in [[Lithuania]], sometime between 1734 and 1736. We also know that around 17 or 18 years of age (1751-1753), he went to [[Hamburg]] to study [[German language|German]], [[Latin]], and [[Greek language|Greek]], as well as the seven sciences.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Debate Over Secular Studies Among the Disciples of the Vilna Gaon|last=Shuchat|first=B. Raphael|publisher=Torah U-Madda Journal|year=1998|isbn=|volume=8|location=|pages=287}}</ref> After returning from [[Hamburg]], he took jobs as rabbi in the towns of Kolyshki and [[Kr\u0101slava]]. He would make many more trips back to [[Hamburg]] later in his life, so he could buy books.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Marriage and life in Slonim ==\nIn around 1766, Ichile Ginshpriker, son of [[Aryeh Leib Epstein]] arranged for his first cousin, Basha bat Ze'ev Wolf and Shimshon to be married. In 1769, Shimshon got a job in [[Slonim]] as the [[Av Beit Din]] (Chief Rabbinical Judge). He kept this position until around 1791. Shimshon was part of the movement of [[Haskalah]] (the Jewish [[Age of Enlightenment]]). When he became [[Av Beit Din]] in [[Slonim]], he began to spread [[Haskalah]] to the whole city. He is regarded as the first to do so in [[Slonim]].\n\n=== Shimshon's library ===\nHe had a library of around 250-300 books that he had collected on his journeys to Hamburg and other cities. People like the [[Vilna Gaon]] and [[Salomon Maimon|Solomon Maimon]] came to Slonim to borrow books from his library. Among Shimshon's prized possessions was the unpublished work by the rabbi, [[Joseph Solomon Delmedigo]], ''Bosmat Bat Shelomoh''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Solomon Maimon's visit ===\nIn the 1770s, a young [[Salomon Maimon|Solomon Maimon]] came from [[Nyasvizh]] to visit the library in search of books on science and medicine. According to Maimon, ''\"As soon as I arrived at the place, I went to the chief rabbi, told him my desire, and begged him earnestly for assistance... He promised to lend me some old German books. The most important among these were an old work on Optics, and Sturm's Physics.\"'' These books inspired Maimon to find \"a key to all secrets of nature\" and look down upon others who didn't know what he knew.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Autobiography of Solomon Maimon: The Complete Translation|last=Maimon|first=Solomon|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2019|isbn=0691163855|location=|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref>\n[[File:Solomon maimon.gif|thumb|[[Salomon Maimon|Solomon Maimon]]]]\n\n=== Meeting with Baruch Schick of Shklov ===\n\nLater on in 1778, upon the recommendation of the [[Vilna Gaon]], Baruch Schick of Shklov (1744-1808) asked Shimshon to write an approbation to his Hebrew translation of ''[[Euclid's Elements]]'', Sefer Oklidus. Shimshon obliged and had much praise for Baruch and his book. Several other rabbis from [[The Hague]] and [[Amsterdam]] contributed an approbation as well. Shimshon's words followed the same theme that Schick wrote, ''\u201cBlessed is your logic, and it will bear forth more blessing, for in your book you have refuted the claims our enemies level against us, saying \u2018where is your wisdom and your learning in the eyes of the nations?\u2019 Jacob will not be ashamed, for the land will be filled with knowledge, as the waters cover the sea.\u201d'' <ref>{{Cite book|title=Seductive Science and the Emergence of the Secular Jewish Intellectual|last=Feiner|first=Shmuel|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2002|isbn=|location=United Kingdom|pages=129}}</ref> What Shimshon was referring to was that [[Jews|Jewish]] people were being thought of as being uneducated and ignorant. What Shimshon wanted to do, was to bring science and other subjects into [[Jews|Jewish]] people's everyday lives, so they could be thought more highly of.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Chronicles and Commentaries: More Explorations of Jewish Life and Learning|last=Segal|first=Eliezer|publisher=Quid Pro Books|year=2015|isbn=9781610278232|location=|pages=|chapter=Non-Euclidean Theocracy}}</ref>[[File:Sefer Oklidus (Euclid's Elements) - Approbation.jpg|thumb|Approbation by Shimshon ben Mordechai of Slonim in Sefer Oklidus (Euclid's Elements Hebrew Translation).]]\n\n=== Jeremy Bentham's visit ===\nIn 1787, the English philosopher, [[Jeremy Bentham]] was going to visit his brother, Samuel in Krichev, when he spent the night in Slonim. As he writes in his journal, all of the inns were full, so he was forced to spend the night with a rabbi that kept a hardware store. He goes on to describe the rabbi's home and that he had two bookcases with \"not fewer than 250 or 300 Vols.\". Bentham also talked about how the rabbi possessed a copy of ''[[Euclid's Elements]]'' and also a manuscript on astronomy which contained a diagram, that the rabbi told him was his own work. Historians have figured out that this was the same rabbi of Slonim as the one who wrote an approbation to Sefer Oklidus and helped Solomon Maimon's desire for books, Rabbi Shimshon ben Mordechai of Slonim.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Touch of Grace: Studies in Ashkenazi Culture, Woman's History, and the Languages of the Jews Presented to Chava Turniansky|last=Bartal|first=Israel|publisher=Shazar|year=2013|isbn=|location=Jerusalem|pages=215, 221\u2013226|chapter=Jeremy Bentham and Samson of Slonim: Two Book Lovers' Story}}</ref>\n== The fire, leaving for K\u00f6nigsberg, and death ==\nSometime in the late 1780s, after Bentham's visit, a fire started in the thatch roof of Shimshon's house. It eventually consumed everything in his house including all of his books and his own manuscripts. He became stricken with grief. It is said that after the fire, \"Shimshon eulogized his loss in the synagogue and cried bitter tears.\" <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://onthemainline.blogspot.com/2011/06/some-notes-about-vilna-gaons-librarian.html|title=On the Main Line: Some notes about the Vilna Gaon's librarian, or, Math is fun.|last=Macdowell|first=Mississippi Fred|date=2011-06-13|website=On the Main Line|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> In 1791, after the fire, he left town for a spot as an [[Av Beit Din]] in the town of K\u00f6nigsberg. By that point, Shimshon was sick and very tired. He only served there for a couple years until his passing in 1794.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Descendants ==\nShimshon's descendants mostly settled in [[Kosava, Belarus|Kosava]]. They adopted the surname, Karelitz after the town of [[Karelichy]]. Some of his most famous descendants were the Rabbi [[Avrohom Yeshaya Karelitz]] (Author of the Chazon Ish), Rabbi [[Nissim Karelitz]], and Rabbi [[Chaim Kanievsky|Shmaryahu Yosef Chaim Kanievsky]].<gallery>\nFile:Chazon Ish.jpg|Rabbi Avrohom Yeshaya Karelitz (The Chazon Ish)\nFile:\u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05e0\u05d9\u05e1\u05d9\u05dd \u05e7\u05e8\u05dc\u05d9\u05e5 \u05e9\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d0.jpg|Rabbi Nissim Karelitz\nFile:Chaim Kanievsky.jpg|Rabbi Shmaryahu Yosef Chaim Kanievsky\n</gallery>\n\n== Legacy ==\nAll of Shimshon's books and his own manuscripts were destroyed in the aforementioned fire. This unfortunately limits our ability to hear the voice of Shimshon as a scholar. In his family's tradition he was known as \"a scholar and [[Kabbalah|Kabbalist]], an astronomer and philosopher, accomplished in all seven sciences, the author of many books, on the [[exoteric]] and the [[Western esotericism|esoteric]], and the chokhmot.\" <ref>{{Cite book|title=The Jewish Enlightenment|last=Feiner|first=Shmuel|publisher=University of Penn Press|year=2011|isbn=0812221729|location=United States|pages=24\u201325}}</ref> Shimshon was also remembered for bringing [[Haskalah]] to [[Slonim]] as well as being a very ardent [[Misnagdim|Mitnagdim]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He also encouraged bringing education into every Jew's everyday lives. He is regarded as being one of the most influential rabbis of [[Slonim]], alongside [[Moses ben Isaac Judah Lima]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Notable associates ==\n\n* Shlomo ben Joshua, [[Salomon Maimon|Solomon Maimon]] (1753-1800) [[Germans|German]] philosopher\n* Rabbi Elijah ben Solomon Zalman, [[Vilna Gaon]] (1720-1797) leader of [[Misnagdim|Mitnagdim]] and [[Haskalah]]\n* Rabbi Baruch ben Jacob Schick, Baruch Schick of Shklov (1744-1808) one of the pioneers of [[Haskalah]] and author\n*Rabbi Aryeh Leib ben Mordechai Epstein of [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], [[Aryeh Leib Epstein]] of [[K\u00f6nigsberg]] (1708-1775) rabbi and author of ''Or ha-Shanim''\n* Rabbi Yitzhak ben Aryeh Leib [[Epstein]], Ichile Ginshpriker of Slonim (1730-1807) Basha (Shimshon's wife's) first cousin. Son of Rabbi [[Aryeh Leib Epstein]] of [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n* Getzel Kressel (1911-1986) [[Israelis|Israeli]] author\n* [[Samuel Joseph Fuenn]] (1818-1891) [[Russians|Russian]] scholar\n* Menachem Mendel Frankfurter (1742-1823) founder of the [[Talmud Torah]] in [[Hamburg]] and grandfather of [[Samson Raphael Hirsch]].\n* Eliezer Segal (1950\u2013present) [[Canadians|Canadian]] professor\n* Rabbi Ephraim ben Shlomo Zalman [[Epstein]] of [[Vilnius|Vilna]] rabbi and author of <u>Gevurot ha-Ari</u>. Great-grandson of Rabbi [[Aryeh Leib Epstein]] of [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]\n* Kalman Lichtenstein (1899-?) author of <u>Pinkas [[Slonim]]</u> (Memorial book of Slonim)\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Zinberg, Israel (1988), ''Italian Jewry in the Renaissance Era.'' Ktav Pub Inc. p.&nbsp;174.\n* Nadler, Allan (1997) ''The Faith of the Mithnagdim: Rabbinic Responses to Hasidic Rapture.'' Johns Hopkins University Press. p.&nbsp;137.\n\n== External links ==\n\n* https://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/slonim/Ledger.html\n* http://www.karelitzfamily.com/ Family tree of Shimshon's descendants\n* https://people.ucalgary.ca/~elsegal/Shokel/130607_Euclid.html\n\n[[Category:18th-century Jewish theologians]]\n[[Category:1794 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Slonim]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rabbi Shimshon ben Mordechai of Slonim\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 1734 or 1736\n| birth_place        = Lithuania, Poland-Lithuania\n| death_date         = 1794\n| death_place        = K\u00f6nigsberg, Prussia\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = Samson of Slonim\n| occupation         = Av Beit Din of Slonim and K\u00f6nigsberg, scientist, astronomer, philosopher, mathematician\n| years_active       = 1769-1794\n| era                = 18th-century philosophy\n| known_for          = Haskalah Movement, Misnagdim Movement, Approbation of Sefer Oklidus\n| movement           = Haskalah, Misnagdim\n| opponents          = Hasidic Jews\n| spouse             = Basha bat Ze'ev Wolf\n| children           = Gershon Zelig of Kosava\n| father             = Mordechai\n| family             = Karelitz\n| Influence          = Vilna Gaon\n}}\n'''Shimshon (Samson) ben Mordechai of Slonim''' (c. 1734/1736 \u2013 1794), was an 18th-century rabbi, philosopher, mathematician, and scientist. He was one of the  leaders of [[Haskalah]] and the [[Misnagdim]], and was greatly influenced by the Vilna Gaon. He was the [[Av Beit Din]] of [[Slonim]] and [[K\u00f6nigsberg]] and is thought to have been descended from Shimshon Loew ben Bezalel, the [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel|Maharal of Prague]]'s brother through his grandson, [[Samson ben Pesah Ostropoli]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Pinkas Slonim [Memorial Book of Slonim]|last=Lichtenstein|first=Kalman|publisher=Irgun \u02bbole Slonim be-Yi\u015bra\u02bcel|year=1961|isbn=|volume=1|location=Tel Aviv|pages=33\u201339}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and early adulthood ==\nNot that much is known about his early life. We do know that he was born in [[Lithuania]], sometime between 1734 and 1736. We also know that around 17 or 18 years of age (1751-1753), he went to [[Hamburg]] to study [[German language|German]], [[Latin]], and [[Greek language|Greek]], as well as the seven sciences.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Deb